column3: The task took a lot longer than advertised in the HIT.
I believe the estimated time should be adjusted. I completed the task at the 70 minute mark which I believe is way more than the estimated time.
it was much longer than stated
I enjoyed this task very much
Instructions were clear and very easy to understand.
I only switched tabs to check the time or to check email.
keep a progress bar of how many are left visible

Definitely easier to tell when there was a pause if the balls were moving faster rather than when it was slower. I know I did terribly at the very beginning -- probably try to discard some of my early trials because when I saw the pause I panicked and completely failed to hit the spacebar. Sometimes I was really confident about the fact that I saw a pause, but I wasn't confident at all in terms of my spacebar timing. Like my reaction times must have been pretty bad. Beautiful stimuli though,  Tristan! In my opinion, the size of the videos was a little bit small. Maybe would be better to be a little larger than credit card width.
Someone shared their screen in a zoom I had open so I could immediately join upon completion and it automatically switched to that screen I'm sorry!

I found the study really interesting! I'm not really what was being measured, though perhaps it could be data to train an AI at recognizing subtle movements. There was some information that could have been provided that would have made it slightly easier, though I think it was withheld on purpose (i.e. whether there could be multiple pauses per video, whether the pauses between videos could differ in speed, etc). Overall though, the study was super interesting! By the way, the screen at the beginning which asked me to input my Prolific ID flashed by too quickly so I wasn't able to put it in. Here it is now just in case it wasn't recorded: 5fcfcdb04fcda8132fd90203
It would be great, for the example/instruction videos, if we were able to replay them or have a little extra time to read the text that goes with them before the video starts playing.

96 clips might be a tad excessive for one session however I completely understand why due to the nature of the study. Maybe next time the study could have two parts to it to ensure the user is not bored of doing the same thing for 20-25 minutes. On the whole it was pretty fun and interesting so no major complaints from me, thanks for hosting the study.
The screen asking me to enter my prolific ID didn't allow me to before moving on; it is 5d3cfeabbaf11000151ed4cd

The pauses felt very subtle - I also liked the ones where the ball comes back out of the tube after barely resting on the tube lift - it seems like that could be interpreted as a "pause", so I indicated my non-confidence on those situations.
The study was one of the best long studys I have taken part in. Kept me engaged.

At the beginning when I had to input my Prolific ID, I switched to the Prolific website to copy my ID but when I went back to the survey, it moved on to the next page. My Prolific ID is: 5f2dad07a2eef40aaef6edb6
I really enjoyed this - kept my concentration at full level!
It was very long so quite hard to stay concentrated.

This was a very interesting experiment, and I actually enjoyed it to be honest. It tested my observational skills, reaction time and sometimes made me think twice on whether my internet was slow/lagging, after which I would remember that the pauses were part of the experiment.
Thanks for letting me participate!
No further comments. All the best with this project. Stay safe.
The survey is very simple and fun.

In response to the question above, I did switch tabs at the start of the experiment when I was instructed to enter my prolific ID. Unfortunately when I went back to the study to enter in my ID, it had already changed screens and I was unable to paste my ID. That was the only time I switched tabs. My prolific ID is - 5f02825de3eda5141350189f

Thank you for this opportunity!
I enjoyed the task, thank you!
Interesting study! I enjoyed completing it.
I took breaks during the task BUT watched the entire video, up to the point where I saw the pause (if there was one).
I did watch all of the videos, but I took a break in the middle to go and make tea.

It was very interesting to partake in this study. Often I had to decide what was the best point in a transition. An example of this is would be deciding to include when a ball went off screen. Thank you, stay safe and healthy, and lastly good luck on the study!!

Got a bit lethargic by the end of it as some were repeated, also was unusual to understand and not clear where you had already pressed for a change of event. Also, when the ball is falling or moving fast the frames always show the ball in different places when you flick it, so was unclear for a change of event then.
I think they were similar videos for some and i reacted differently each time it confused me

Not sure if it's the program's problem or my keyboard's. Sometimes pressing my enter key leads to pausing the video (which I didn't want to). Also I did not see any purple border even when I replayed the video after submitting my responses.
I'm not sure that I totally understood the task. I hope I helped nonetheless.
I think, as its a computer study, it could have been easier to have click-able buttons for the event, pause, fast forward etc.
I wasn't sure which 'events' were events. I'm not sure I counted some things as events so hopefully I still did what you needed me to.
I wasn't sure what was defined as an 'event change'.

I wasn't sure if the course of the video was right for some of them as I had moments where the ball took a while to appear on the screen etc. I judged the event changes as best as I could for these videos.
Interested to know the outcome of the study.

The space bar and frame navigation failed sometimes during some of the tests. ( I am using brave browser). So I did the best I could to capture the event changes. Hope my data helps your research, regardless. :)
I think the study is about attention span and how doing a long task affects performance and our perceptions of our performance. Hope u find interesting results :)
I needed a break from the screen - it was hurting my eyes
I have no further comments or questions.
Thank you, have a lovely day!
most of the distortions are pretty easy to spot apart from the few where it is hard to differentiate between framerate and distortion because the distortion is so minor
The videos were tricky with the shadows
I watched all videos however alt tabbed once or twice before starting the next video.
I got very bored and ended up paying attention to what number I was on by around 36.
Brilliant study - I really enjoyed particpating.

The video clips were made to make you think after the video has occurred and making you recall back and majority of the times questioned yourself whether you have missed the break in the clips that I did not press the spacebar for.
The task was quite long and it became a bit boring after a while. I found myself counting down the number of tasks left until I finished.

I enjoyed the study. On the red balls there was a white spot where the light reflected off, i found it effective to keep my eyes stuck on that spot and track the balls movement trying to detect a pause
I found the scale slightly unclear as I would interpret 'not confident' and 'unsure' as the same thing so I found myself hovering between 'unsure' and 'very confident' more
I switched tabs a couple of times, but never while a video was playing. There were also a few times I thought I saw a pause, but felt it was too late to press space
Hard to tell sometimes if it was an intentional pause or a display glitch.
Very fun survey! Thanks for the opportunity!
The task did glitch out when I was at video 30 or so. The video did not load up. I just had to close the window and reload it again but it did mean that I had to go back to the first video.
It was very interesting, I had my eyes on that ball like a hawk!
I think more trials would be good to better prepare the candidate for the initial videos.
Found some of them hard to tell whether it paused or not
really interesting experiment, would've liked a break half way through

I found my reaction times were sometimes faster and some slower depending on how quick my brain processed the pauses (and whether or not there was actually a distortion.) Sometimes it was easier to see the pauses/distortions when the ball rolled fast and other times it was easier when it rolled slowly.

The prompt at the beginning of the study (before it started) when it asked me for my prolific ID disappeared as I switched tabs to copy and paste, here is my prolific ID in case it wasn't registered - 5f99e7c14c53720c56a220d0
All instructions were clear and easy to follow. Experiment ran smoothly with no problems.
The pressing of the spacebar was delayed. The red frame did not appear immediately after pressing the spacebar, delay was by 1 full second
Good fun, thanks for the invite :)
One of the videos, I think number 78 if I recall correctly had a double countdown for some reason. Also I wonder if some videos had multiple pauses and we were not told to look for these
